WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.000
 Hello and welcome to our lecture on Object-Oriented Programming in JavaScript.

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:12.000
 I teach Object-Oriented Programming in Python, in PHP, and in JavaScript.

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:15.000
 And I use the same slides over and over and over again.

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:20.000
 And that's because Object-Oriented concepts are the same.

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:24.000
 So if you've taken other classes from me, you've seen some of these slides.

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:29.000
 They're adapted a little bit from JavaScript because JavaScript's Object-Oriented pattern is particularly awesome, right?

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:34.000
 But there's this concept of a class, which is like a template.

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:38.000
 There's a concept of code and data in a class.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:40.000
 Whether you call the code method or message is up to you.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:43.000
 Whether you call the data attributes or fields.

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:45.000
 And then an object is an instance of the class.

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:52.000
 And so the cookie cutter is the shape that's the class and the cookie itself that can be specialized.

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:56.000
 And it's an instance. Millions of cookies come from one cookie cutter.

00:00:56.000 --> 00:00:58.000
 And that's Object-Oriented.

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:06.000
 So the key is the craft of it is building the cookie cutter so that it makes awesome cookies.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:10.000
 So the class, like I said, is the template. It's a blueprint.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:16.000
 It's not the actual thing, but it is the precise instructions on how to make the thing.

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:21.000
 An instance is once you make the cookie, you can have different frosting on it.

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:24.000
 You can have all kinds of other things.

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:31.000
 You can make subclasses, which is what we do for inheritance, which makes specialized versions of the class.

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:33.000
 Now, the methods are the code.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:39.000
 So in classic programming, we think of like code and data structures, algorithms and data structures.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:45.000
 Data structures are the shape of data and algorithms are the shape of the code, the way the code is made to work.

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:50.000
 The methods are the algorithms that make up the code part of every object.

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:56.000
 Every object has code and data, and often the code works on the data that's inside the object.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:03.000
 Some Object-Oriented sort of schools of thought use method, and some use message.

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:07.000
 The more purist folks tend to use messages, like you're sending a message.

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:11.000
 Here's the object, not the class. You're sending a message to the object.

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:15.000
 I tend to use method because method is a bit of code that lives in there.

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:22.000
 That's just because I think of things from like Fortran or C, very procedural way of thinking.

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:25.000
 So objects in JavaScript are a little different.

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:32.000
 And if you've seen me talk about objects in Python or objects in PHP or even objects in Java,

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:37.000
 which I taught a lot of time ago, or C++, they're very different.

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:41.000
 And the key thing is it certainly is a storing reuse pattern.

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:47.000
 It is a mechanism to create data and code and put it into one kind of reusable thing.

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:54.000
 But the key thing is that the function keyword is actually, in a sense, an executable statement.

00:02:54.000 --> 00:03:01.000
 And you can take and use the function keyword, and the function is, in a sense,

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:05.000
 calling a function that causes code to come back to you.

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:11.000
 So you can have the function create code and then assign it into the variable.

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:13.000
 These are called first-class functions.

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:20.000
 And it has to do with the fact that in first-class functions, you have this symmetry between code and data.

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:22.000
 The code is just data.

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:30.000
 And of all of the modern programming languages, Lisp really was the original code-data kind of duality.

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:37.000
 There is very, very, very much throwback to the Lisp tradition of data and code look the same way

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:39.000
 or can be treated the same way.

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:43.000
 You can have X as a variable and you can assign it to be 42.

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:47.000
 You can have it be a string or you can have it be a function that adds two numbers together.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:51.000
 And it's just X. And that is kind of elegant.

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:56.000
 So that's called first-class functions in that functions themselves are the code.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:00.000
 So the code in systems is manipulable as data.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:04.000
 Copy around, use it, reuse it, et cetera.

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:10.000
 So up next, we're going to take a look at how we put together a sample class in JavaScript.

